[1] Saudi Arabia: new fatality, Ministry of Public Health
Date: Sun 26 May 2013
Source: Ministry of Public Health [edited]
http://www.moh.gov.sa/en/Ministry/MediaCenter/News/Pages/News-2013-05-26-003.aspx


MOH: A new coronavirus case passed away in Al-Ahsa Governorate -- 26 May 2013
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Within the framework of the epidemiological surveillance of the novel coronavirus (MERS-CoV), the Ministry of Health (MOH) has announced the death of one patient of the previously infected cases in Al-Ahsa governorate. It is noteworthy that this woman, aged 81 years, was suffering from chronic kidney failure as well as other chronic diseases.

In the same vein, the MOH has pointed out that no positive cases of this virus have been recorded in Al-Ahsa governorate since [18 May 2013]. Meanwhile, lab tests have been conducted for 49 samples during the past 24 hours from different regions, and the results proved negative.

Furthermore, MOH has declared that 9 cases of this virus have recovered and left the health facilities.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[New information provided by the Ministry of Public Health includes the confirmation of another fatality, raising the number of laboratory confirmed fatalities attributable to MERS-CoV to 23, out of 44 laboratory confirmed cases as of 26 May 2013 (case fatality rate of 52 per cent). Of the 23 fatalities, 18 have occurred in Saudi Arabia.

Other new information includes the mention of the number of specimens processed for MERS-CoV testing -- 49 in the preceding 24 hours, suggesting there is extensive surveillance ongoing in Saudi Arabia to identify all possible cases of infection with the MERS-CoV.

For a map of Saudi Arabia, see http://healthmap.org/r/1HAJ. - Mod.MPP]

******
[2] Saudi Arabia: new fatality, newswire
Date: Sun 26 May 2013
Source: Arab News [edited]
http://www.arabnews.com/news/452989


Elderly woman is 18th MERS-CoV fatality in KSA
----------------------------------------------
The octogenarian woman in Al-Ahsa who had contracted the SARS-like coronavirus has died, raising the death toll in the Kingdom to 18 and the world total at 23, a Ministry of Health statement said on Sunday [26 May 2013].

"An 81 year old woman who was suffering from kidney failure as well as other chronic illnesses has died" in the eastern Al-Ahsa region after contracting the virus, the statement said.

Now called by the MERS-CoV by the World Health Organization, short for Middle East respiratory [syndrome] coronavirus, the new virus is from the same family as those that cause common colds and the one that caused the deadly outbreak of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) that emerged in Asia in 2003.

On [18 May 2013], the WHO included the 81 year old woman in Al-Ahsa as case number 41 in its list of MERS-CoV victims worldwide. It cited a report of the Saudi MOH saying the woman became ill on [28 Apr 2013], and was "currently in critical but stable condition."

"She was in the same health care facility previously identified as the focus of this outbreak, from [8 to 28 Apr 2013]," it added.

The facility referred to had earlier been identified by health officials as a hospital in Hofuf town in Al-Ahsa.

In its latest update on [23 May 2013], the WHO placed the worldwide total of laboratory-confirmed cases of MERS-CoV infection at 44 since the virus was discovered by scientists in September 2012.

Saudi Arabia counts by far the most cases, with 30 confirmed infections and 18 fatalities, while cases have also been detected in Jordan, Qatar, Tunisia, UAE, Germany, Britain, and France.

Most cases have been registered in the east, with the ministry saying that most of those who died were "elderly people with chronic illnesses."

The 17th fatality was a 63 year old Syrian man in the central province of Qassim, the 1st non-Saudi in the kingdom to catch MERS-CoV.

Of those infected in Saudi Arabia, 2 were health workers who caught the virus from patients in their care, the 1st evidence of such transmission within a hospital, WHO said earlier.

WHO said that much uncertainty remained surrounding the virus, stressing that it aimed to work closely with Saudi Arabia, Tunisia, and perhaps other Middle Eastern countries to determine how great the risk is.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Additional information provided in the above newswire is the nationality of the non-Saudi Arabian fatal case reported on 22 May 2013 (see ProMED-mail post, MERS-CoV - Eastern Mediterranean (08): Saudi Arabia, new case, fatal, RFI 20130522.1731245), a Syrian national. It is not clear if this individual lived in Saudi Arabia, or was a temporary visitor. From the discussion on this case, it seemed clear the individual was considered to have been infected with the MERS-CoV while in Saudi Arabia. - Mod.MPP]

